# Rails testing (Minitest)

## Where tests live

| Kind | Path | Use for |
|------|------|--------|
| Model / unit | `test/models/` | Validations, scopes, enums, instance logic, plain Ruby collaborators |
| Service-style POROs | `test/services/` (or `test/models/` if colocated) | Objects that orchestrate models or I/O |
| HTTP / routing | `test/controllers/` or `test/integration/` / `test/requests/` | Status, redirects, assigns, Turbo streams, auth |
| Jobs | `test/jobs/` | Enqueued behavior, side effects (with `perform_enqueued_jobs` when needed) |
| Mailers | `test/mailers/` | Headers, bodies, delivery when not default-skipped |
| Browser | `test/system/` | End-to-end flows; Capybara + real browser (slower, fewer tests) |

Prefer **request/integration tests** over controller unit tests when exercising the full stack (params ŌåÆ response) matches how the app is used.

## Design of each test

- **One obvious behavior** per test; name tests so failures read like specs (`test "rejects negative calories when final"`).
- **Arrange / act / assert**ŌĆökeep setup visible; extract helpers only when it improves clarity.
- **Do not test the framework** (e.g. that `validates` exists); test **your** rules and branches.
- Use **`assert_changes` / `assert_no_changes` / `assert_difference`** for counts and attributes instead of manual before/after when it fits.
- For **time**, use `travel_to` / `freeze_time` helpers so tests are deterministic.

## Data: fixtures and factories

- This project loads **`fixtures :all`**ŌĆöprefer fixtures for shared baseline records; add only the rows a test needs via labels or inline creation when fixtures are too heavy.
- When creating records in a test, use **valid attributes**; avoid relying on implicit DB defaults unless that is what you are testing.

## Boundaries and I/O

- **Stub or fake** at system boundaries (HTTP clients, RubyLLM, payment APIs)ŌĆönot the code under test. Use thin test doubles; restore behavior in `ensure` or helpers like `with_stubbed_instance_method` in `test_helper.rb`.
- **Do not** stub the method you are trying to verify unless the test is explicitly about the callerŌĆÖs reaction to that dependency.

## Request, Turbo, and Hotwire

- Assert **response code**, **flash**, **redirect location**, and **Turbo Stream** bodies (`assert_select` / `response.body`) where the feature matters.
- Prefer following redirects only when the scenario requires it (`follow_redirect!` in integration tests).

## System tests

- Cover **critical user paths** (happy path + one important failure), not every permutation.
- Rely on CapybaraŌĆÖs **matching and retrying**; avoid `sleep` except when interacting with something the driver cannot observe (rare).
- Keep selectors **stable** (`data-testid` or roles) rather than brittle CSS chains.

## Speed and stability

- Avoid unnecessary **full-stack** tests when a request or model test suffices.
- Keep tests **independent**: no order dependence; do not share mutable class-level state without reset.
- Match **CI**: `bin/rails test`; use `db:test:prepare` when the schema changed. System tests: `bin/rails test:system`.

## Style

- Follow **Standard** Ruby style; keep helpers in `test_helper.rb` or `test/support/` when reused across many files.
